The paper deals with generative network training, which is a topic that falls under the broad category of machine learning. Specifically, the paper proposes a method for minimizing the Wasserstein distance between a generative network and a target distribution. This places the paper in the sub-category of machine learning known as "deep learning" (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper uses the MNIST dataset, which is a commonly used dataset in computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the suitability of the Wasserstein distance for certain tasks, which suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of regression in the proposed method suggests a connection to neural networks (cs.NE), and the use of optimal transport theory suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT).
